 point for new readers of Boccaccio’s masterpiece. The readings demonstrate how Boccaccio engaged in rethinking or elaborating on the heritage of Western literature and thought, including the Bible; the works of Dante; the Roman literary, rhetorical, and legal tradition; the writings of the Church Fathers; and the ideas of scholastic theologians. These lecturae employ a range of methodologies that account for both historical and theoretical issues in their engagement with Boccaccio's poetic and ethical project in the Decameron.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aDay 6.  aDecameron.  aGiotto.  aGiovanni Boccaccio.  aGuido Cavalcanti.  aMedieval Italian novella.  aMotto.  aTale of Madonna.  alecturae.  amedieval short story.  aplague.  aquarantine.  ashort story collections.  astorytelling.1 aArmstrong, Guyda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarański, Zygmunt G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCardillo, Giulia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarravetta, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuilleanáin, Cormac Ó., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeng, Aileen A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKriesel, James C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLettiero, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLummus, David , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLummus, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPiciché, Bernardo, econtributor.4c